In [3]:
from matplotlib import image

base_dir = 'projectdata'

loaded_images = list()
for fish_family in listdir(base_dir):
	fish_family_list = list()
	fish_family_dir = base_dir + '/' + fish_family + '/'
	for picture in listdir(fish_family_dir):
		img_data = image.imread(fish_family_dir + picture)
		fish_family_list.append(img_data)
	loaded_images.append(fish_family_list)
	print('Fish Family: ' + fish_family + " | Item Count: " + str(len(fish_family_list)))

Fish Family: Triggerfish | Item Count: 215

In [4]:
from keras.preprocessing import image

visualization_data_generator = ImageDataGenerator(rescale=1./255)
visualization_dataset = visualization_data_generator.flow_from_directory(
        base_dir,
        target_size=(256, 256),
        batch_size=20,
        class_mode='categorical',
        color_mode='rgb')
class_dictionary = visualization_dataset.class_indices

i = 0
figure = plt.figure(figsize=(12, 12))
columns = 5
rows = 6
ax = []
for batch in visualization_data_generator.flow_from_directory(
        base_dir,
        target_size=(256, 256),
        batch_size=1,
        class_mode='categorical',
        color_mode='rgb'):
    i += 1

    lbl_index = np.nonzero(batch[1][0] == 1)[0][0]
    label = list(class_dictionary.keys())[list(class_dictionary.values()).index(lbl_index)]
    
    ax.append( figure.add_subplot(rows, columns, i) )
    imgplot = plt.imshow(image.array_to_img(batch[0][0,:,:,:]),cmap='gray')
    ax[-1].set_title(label)
    
    if i % (columns*rows) == 0:
        break
plt.setp(ax, xticks=[], yticks=[])
    
plt.show()

Found 1051 images belonging to 5 classes.

In [5]:
import os, shutil, pathlib

original_dir = pathlib.Path("projectdata")
new_base_dir = pathlib.Path("projectdatasplit")

def make_subset(subset_name, start_index, end_index):
  for category in ("Butterflyfish", "Clownfish", "Lionfish", "Parrotfish", "Triggerfish"):
    dir = new_base_dir / subset_name / category
    os.makedirs(dir)
    fnames = [f"{category} - {i}.jpeg" for i in range(start_index, end_index)]
    for fname in fnames:
      shutil.copyfile(src=original_dir / category / fname, dst=dir / fname)

make_subset("train", start_index=1, end_index=130)
make_subset("validation", start_index=130, end_index=190)
make_subset("test", start_index=190, end_index=200)

# data_generator = ImageDataGenerator(rescale=1./255, validation_split=0.2)
data_generator = ImageDataGenerator(rescale=1./255)

train_dataset = data_generator.flow_from_directory(
  # base_dir,
  new_base_dir / "train",
  target_size=(256, 256),
  batch_size=20,
  class_mode='categorical',
  # subset='training',
  color_mode='rgb')

validation_dataset = data_generator.flow_from_directory(
  # base_dir,
  new_base_dir / "validation",
  target_size=(256, 256),
  batch_size=20,
  class_mode='categorical',
  # subset='validation',
  color_mode='rgb')

test_dataset = data_generator.flow_from_directory(
  # base_dir,
  new_base_dir / "test",
  target_size=(256, 256),
  batch_size=20,
  class_mode='categorical',
  # subset='validation',
  color_mode='rgb')



class_dictionary = train_dataset.class_indices
print(class_dictionary)

#this one was stalling out around ~70% after ~100 epochs, 
#but only has 611 params total

model = Sequential()
model.add( Conv2D( 4, ( 3, 3 ), activation = 'relu', input_shape = (256, 256, 3) ) )
model.add( MaxPool2D(4, 4) )
model.add( Conv2D( 4, ( 3, 3 ), activation = 'relu' ) )
model.add( MaxPool2D(4, 4) )
model.add( Conv2D( 4, ( 3, 3 ), activation = 'relu' ) )
model.add( MaxPool2D(4, 4) )
model.add( Conv2D( 4, ( 3, 3 ), activation = 'relu' ) )

model.add( Flatten() )
model.add( Dense( 5, activation = 'relu' ) )
model.add( Dense( 5, activation = 'softmax' ) )
model.summary()
# plot_model(model, show_layer_names=True, show_shapes=True)

#plot the learning curve of the attempt at an overfitted model
#this one was stalling out around ~70% after ~100 epochs, 
#but only has 611 params total
#not a big enough network to overfit

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
print(history_4444.history.keys())
title = '4x4x4x4 Conv Layers with (4,4) Maxpooling'

plt.plot(history_4444.history['accuracy'])
plt.ylabel('Accuracy')
plt.xlabel('Epoch')
plt.title(title)
plt.legend(['Complete Dataset'], loc='lower right')
plt.show()


plt.plot(history_4444.history['loss'])
plt.ylabel('Loss')
plt.xlabel('Epoch')
plt.title(title)
plt.legend(['Complete Dataset'], loc='upper right')
plt.show()

weights, biases = model.layers[0].get_weights()

from keras import callbacks
import tensorflow
import keras

a = tensorflow.keras.callbacks.ModelCheckpoint(filepath='model.h5', monitor='val_loss', save_best_only=True)
b = keras.callbacks.EarlyStopping(monitor = 'val_accuracy', patience=20)

history_8644 = model.fit(
    x=train_dataset,
    validation_data=validation_dataset,
    callbacks=[a, b],
    steps_per_epoch=30, #1000 images / batch size of 20 = ~50 (https://stackoverflow.com/questions/49922252/choosing-number-of-steps-per-epoch)
    epochs=500)

In [ ]:
import numpy as np

data_generator = ImageDataGenerator(rescale=1./255)

dataset = data_generator.flow_from_directory(
        base_dir,
        target_size=(256, 256),
        batch_size=20,
        class_mode='categorical',
        color_mode='rgb')

samples = 1051
##Convert the 3 channel rgb to 8 channels (3 RGB + 5 Fish)
x_train = np.zeros(shape=(samples, 256, 256, 8))
y_train = np.zeros(shape=(samples, 5))

print(x_train[0, 0, 0, :])
print(x_train[0, 0, 0, 3:])

cur = 0
complete = False

for batch in dataset:
  if complete:
    break
  images = batch[0]
  labels = batch[1]
  for im in range(len(images)):
    existing = images[im]
    newchannel = np.zeros( (256, 256, 1) ) + labels[im]
    x = np.concatenate( (existing, newchannel), axis = -1)
    x_train[cur] = x
    y_train[cur] = labels[im]
    cur += 1
    if cur == samples:
      complete = True
      break

print(x_train[:5, 0, 0, 3:])


print(x_train[0, 0, 0, 3:])
print(x_train[1, 0, 0, 3:])
print(x_train[2, 0, 0, 3:])
print(x_train[3, 0, 0, 3:])
print(x_train[4, 0, 0, 3:])

model = Sequential()
model.add( Conv2D( 4, ( 3, 3 ), activation = 'relu', input_shape = (256, 256, 8) ) )

from keras import callbacks
import tensorflow
import keras

#ok, now lets try this with the validation dataset

model = Sequential()
model.add( Conv2D( 8, ( 3, 3 ), activation = 'relu', input_shape = (256, 256, 3) ) )
model.add( MaxPool2D(4, 4) )
model.add( Conv2D( 6, ( 3, 3 ), activation = 'relu' ) )
model.add( MaxPool2D(4, 4) )
model.add( Conv2D( 4, ( 3, 3 ), activation = 'relu' ) )
model.add( MaxPool2D(4, 4) )
model.add( Conv2D( 4, ( 3, 3 ), activation = 'relu' ) )

model.add( Flatten() )
model.add( Dense( 5, activation = 'relu' ) )
model.add( Dense( 5, activation = 'softmax' ) )
model.summary()

model.compile( optimizer = 'adam', loss = 'categorical_crossentropy', metrics = [ 'accuracy' ] )

a = tensorflow.keras.callbacks.ModelCheckpoint(filepath='model.h5', monitor='val_loss', save_best_only=True)
b = keras.callbacks.EarlyStopping(monitor = 'val_accuracy', patience=20)

history_8644 = model.fit(
    x=train_dataset,
    validation_data=validation_dataset,
    callbacks=[a, b],
    steps_per_epoch=30, #1000 images / batch size of 20 = ~50 (https://stackoverflow.com/questions/49922252/choosing-number-of-steps-per-epoch)
    epochs=500)

##plot the learning curve of the overfitted model
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

title = '8x6x4x4 Conv Layers with Maxpooling'

plt.plot(history_8644.history['accuracy'], "b", label="Training")
plt.plot(history_8644.history['val_accuracy'], "r", label="Validation")
plt.ylabel('Accuracy')
plt.xlabel('Epoch')
plt.title(title)
plt.legend(loc='lower right')
plt.show()

plt.plot(history_8644.history['loss'], "b", label="Training")
plt.plot(history_8644.history['val_loss'], "r", label="Validation")
plt.ylabel('Loss')
plt.xlabel('Epoch')
plt.title(title)
plt.legend(loc='upper right')
plt.show()



##Load the weights of the best model acquired in training
model.load_weights('model.h5')

##Observe the results of the model against the test data
test_loss_8644, test_acc_8644 = model.evaluate(
    test_dataset,
    steps=23
)

print(f'Test Acc: {test_acc_8644}\nTest Loss: {test_loss_8644}')

from keras import callbacks
import tensorflow
import keras

#ok, try buggegr

model = Sequential()
model.add( Conv2D( 16, ( 3, 3 ), activation = 'relu', input_shape = (256, 256, 3) ) )
model.add( MaxPool2D(4, 4) )
model.add( Conv2D( 8, ( 3, 3 ), activation = 'relu' ) )
model.add( MaxPool2D(4, 4) )
model.add( Conv2D( 4, ( 3, 3 ), activation = 'relu' ) )
model.add( MaxPool2D(4, 4) )
model.add( Conv2D( 4, ( 3, 3 ), activation = 'relu' ) )

model.add( Flatten() )
model.add( Dense( 5, activation = 'relu' ) )
model.add( Dense( 5, activation = 'softmax' ) )
model.summary()

model.compile( optimizer = 'adam', loss = 'categorical_crossentropy', metrics = [ 'accuracy' ] )

a = tensorflow.keras.callbacks.ModelCheckpoint(filepath='model.h5', monitor='val_loss', save_best_only=True)
b = keras.callbacks.EarlyStopping(monitor = 'val_accuracy', patience=20)

history_16844 = model.fit(
    x=train_dataset,
    validation_data=validation_dataset,
    callbacks=[a, b],
    steps_per_epoch=30, #1000 images / batch size of 20 = ~50 (https://stackoverflow.com/questions/49922252/choosing-number-of-steps-per-epoch)
    epochs=500)

##plot the learning curve of the overfitted model
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

title = '16x8x4x4 Conv Layers with Maxpooling'

plt.plot(history_16844.history['accuracy'], "b", label="Training")
plt.plot(history_16844.history['val_accuracy'], "r", label="Validation")
plt.ylabel('Accuracy')
plt.xlabel('Epoch')
plt.title(title)
plt.legend(loc='lower right')
plt.show()

plt.plot(history_16844.history['loss'], "b", label="Training")
plt.plot(history_16844.history['val_loss'], "r", label="Validation")
plt.ylabel('Loss')
plt.xlabel('Epoch')
plt.title(title)
plt.legend(loc='upper right')
plt.show()

##Load the weights of the best model acquired in training
model.load_weights('model.h5')

##Observe the results of the model against the test data
test_loss_16844, test_acc_16844 = model.evaluate(
    test_dataset,
    steps=5
)

print(f'Test Acc: {test_acc_16844}\nTest Loss: {test_loss_16844}')

from keras import callbacks
import tensorflow
import keras

#ok, try biggegr

model = Sequential()
model.add( Conv2D( 32, ( 3, 3 ), activation = 'relu', input_shape = (256, 256, 3) ) )
model.add( MaxPool2D(4, 4) )
model.add( Conv2D( 16, ( 3, 3 ), activation = 'relu' ) )
model.add( MaxPool2D(4, 4) )
model.add( Conv2D( 16, ( 3, 3 ), activation = 'relu' ) )
model.add( MaxPool2D(4, 4) )
model.add( Conv2D( 4, ( 3, 3 ), activation = 'relu' ) )

model.add( Flatten() )
model.add( Dense( 5, activation = 'relu' ) )
model.add( Dense( 5, activation = 'softmax' ) )
model.summary()

model.compile( optimizer = 'adam', loss = 'categorical_crossentropy', metrics = [ 'accuracy' ] )

a = tensorflow.keras.callbacks.ModelCheckpoint(filepath='model.h5', monitor='val_loss', save_best_only=True)
b = keras.callbacks.EarlyStopping(monitor = 'val_accuracy', patience=20)

history_3216164 = model.fit(
    x=train_dataset,
    validation_data=validation_dataset,
    callbacks=[a, b],
    steps_per_epoch=30, #1000 images / batch size of 20 = ~50 (https://stackoverflow.com/questions/49922252/choosing-number-of-steps-per-epoch)
    epochs=500)

##plot the learning curve of the overfitted model
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

title = '32x16x16x4 Conv Layers with Maxpooling'

plt.plot(history_3216164.history['accuracy'], "b", label="Training")
plt.plot(history_3216164.history['val_accuracy'], "r", label="Validation")
plt.ylabel('Accuracy')
plt.xlabel('Epoch')
plt.title(title)
plt.legend(loc='lower right')
plt.show()

plt.plot(history_3216164.history['loss'], "b", label="Training")
plt.plot(history_3216164.history['val_loss'], "r", label="Validation")
plt.ylabel('Loss')
plt.xlabel('Epoch')
plt.title(title)
plt.legend(loc='upper right')
plt.show()

##Load the weights of the best model acquired in training
model.load_weights('model.h5')

##Observe the results of the model against the test data
test_loss_3216164, test_acc_3216164 = model.evaluate(
    test_dataset)

print(f'Test Acc: {test_acc_3216164}\nTest Loss: {test_loss_3216164}')

from keras import callbacks
import tensorflow
import keras

#ok, maybe even bigger?

model = Sequential()
model.add( Conv2D( 64, ( 3, 3 ), activation = 'relu', input_shape = (256, 256, 3) ) )
model.add( MaxPool2D(4, 4) )
model.add( Conv2D( 32, ( 3, 3 ), activation = 'relu' ) )
model.add( MaxPool2D(4, 4) )
model.add( Conv2D( 16, ( 3, 3 ), activation = 'relu' ) )
model.add( MaxPool2D(4, 4) )
model.add( Conv2D( 4, ( 3, 3 ), activation = 'relu' ) )

model.add( Flatten() )
model.add( Dense( 5, activation = 'relu' ) )
model.add( Dense( 5, activation = 'softmax' ) )
model.summary()

model.compile( optimizer = 'adam', loss = 'categorical_crossentropy', metrics = [ 'accuracy' ] )

a = tensorflow.keras.callbacks.ModelCheckpoint(filepath='model.h5', monitor='val_loss', save_best_only=True)
b = keras.callbacks.EarlyStopping(monitor = 'val_accuracy', patience=20)

history_6432164 = model.fit(
    x=train_dataset,
    validation_data=validation_dataset,
    callbacks=[a, b],
    steps_per_epoch=30, #1000 images / batch size of 20 = ~50 (https://stackoverflow.com/questions/49922252/choosing-number-of-steps-per-epoch)
    epochs=500)

##plot the learning curve of the overfitted model

plt.plot(history_6432164.history['val_accuracy'], "r", label="Validation")

plt.title(title)

plt.show()

plt.plot(history_6432164.history['val_loss'], "r", label="Validation")
plt.ylabel('Loss')
plt.xlabel('Epoch')
plt.title(title)
plt.legend(loc='upper right')
plt.show()

    test_dataset

from keras import callbacks
import tensorflow
import keras

#ok, maybe even bigger?

model = Sequential()
model.add( Conv2D( 64, ( 3, 3 ), activation = 'relu', input_shape = (256, 256, 3) ) )
model.add( MaxPool2D(4, 4) )
model.add( Conv2D( 32, ( 3, 3 ), activation = 'relu' ) )
model.add( MaxPool2D(4, 4) )
model.add( Conv2D( 32, ( 3, 3 ), activation = 'relu' ) )
model.add( MaxPool2D(4, 4) )
model.add( Conv2D( 4, ( 3, 3 ), activation = 'relu' ) )

model.add( Flatten() )
model.add( Dense( 5, activation = 'relu' ) )
model.add( Dense( 5, activation = 'softmax' ) )
model.summary()

model.compile( optimizer = 'adam', loss = 'categorical_crossentropy', metrics = [ 'accuracy' ] )

a = tensorflow.keras.callbacks.ModelCheckpoint(filepath='model.h5', monitor='val_loss', save_best_only=True)
b = keras.callbacks.EarlyStopping(monitor = 'val_accuracy', patience=20)

history_6432324 = model.fit(
    x=train_dataset,
    validation_data=validation_dataset,
    callbacks=[a, b],
    steps_per_epoch=30, #1000 images / batch size of 20 = ~50 (https://stackoverflow.com/questions/49922252/choosing-number-of-steps-per-epoch)
    epochs=500)

##plot the learning curve of the overfitted model
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

title = '64x32x32x4 Conv Layers with Maxpooling'

plt.plot(history_6432324.history['accuracy'], "b", label="Training")
plt.plot(history_6432324.history['val_accuracy'], "r", label="Validation")
plt.ylabel('Accuracy')
plt.xlabel('Epoch')
plt.title(title)
plt.legend(loc='lower right')
plt.show()

plt.plot(history_6432324.history['loss'], "b", label="Training")
plt.plot(history_6432324.history['val_loss'], "r", label="Validation")
plt.ylabel('Loss')
plt.xlabel('Epoch')
plt.title(title)
plt.legend(loc='upper right')
plt.show()


##Load the weights of the best model acquired in training
model.load_weights('model.h5')

##Observe the results of the model against the test data
test_loss_6432324, test_acc_6432324 = model.evaluate(
    test_dataset
)

print(f'Test Acc: {test_acc_6432324}\nTest Loss: {test_loss_6432324}')

from keras import callbacks
import tensorflow
import keras

#ok, maybe even bigger?

model = Sequential()
model.add( Conv2D( 64, ( 3, 3 ), activation = 'relu', input_shape = (256, 256, 3) ) )
model.add( MaxPool2D(4, 4) )
model.add( Conv2D( 64, ( 3, 3 ), activation = 'relu' ) )
model.add( MaxPool2D(4, 4) )
model.add( Conv2D( 32, ( 3, 3 ), activation = 'relu' ) )
model.add( MaxPool2D(4, 4) )
model.add( Conv2D( 4, ( 3, 3 ), activation = 'relu' ) )

model.add( Flatten() )
model.add( Dense( 5, activation = 'relu' ) )
model.add( Dense( 5, activation = 'softmax' ) )
model.summary()

model.compile( optimizer = 'adam', loss = 'categorical_crossentropy', metrics = [ 'accuracy' ] )

a = tensorflow.keras.callbacks.ModelCheckpoint(filepath='model.h5', monitor='val_loss', save_best_only=True)
b = keras.callbacks.EarlyStopping(monitor = 'val_accuracy', patience=20)

history_6464324 = model.fit(
    x=train_dataset,
    validation_data=validation_dataset,
    callbacks=[a, b],
    steps_per_epoch=30, #1000 images / batch size of 20 = ~50 (https://stackoverflow.com/questions/49922252/choosing-number-of-steps-per-epoch)
    epochs=500)

##plot the learning curve of the overfitted model
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

title = '64x64x32x4 Conv Layers with Maxpooling'

plt.plot(history_6464324.history['accuracy'], "b", label="Training")
plt.plot(history_6464324.history['val_accuracy'], "r", label="Validation")
plt.ylabel('Accuracy')
plt.xlabel('Epoch')
plt.title(title)
plt.legend(loc='lower right')
plt.show()

plt.plot(history_6464324.history['loss'], "b", label="Training")
plt.plot(history_6464324.history['val_loss'], "r", label="Validation")
plt.ylabel('Loss')
plt.xlabel('Epoch')
plt.title(title)
plt.legend(loc='upper right')
plt.show()

##Load the weights of the best model acquired in training
model.load_weights('model.h5')

##Observe the results of the model against the test data
test_loss_6464324, test_acc_6464324 = model.evaluate(
    test_dataset
)

print(f'Test Acc: {test_acc_6464324}\nTest Loss: {test_loss_6464324}')

from keras import callbacks
import tensorflow
import keras

#ok, smaller with more layers?

model = Sequential()
model.add( Conv2D( 8, ( 3, 3 ), activation = 'relu', input_shape = (256, 256, 3) ) )
model.add( Conv2D( 8, ( 3, 3 ), activation = 'relu' ) )
model.add( MaxPool2D(4, 4) )
model.add( Conv2D( 8, ( 3, 3 ), activation = 'relu' ) )
model.add( Conv2D( 8, ( 3, 3 ), activation = 'relu' ) )
model.add( MaxPool2D(4, 4) )
model.add( Conv2D( 6, ( 3, 3 ), activation = 'relu' ) )
model.add( Conv2D( 6, ( 3, 3 ), activation = 'relu' ) )
model.add( Conv2D( 4, ( 3, 3 ), activation = 'relu' ) )

model.add( Flatten() )
model.add( Dense( 5, activation = 'relu' ) )
model.add( Dense( 5, activation = 'softmax' ) )
model.summary()

model.compile( optimizer = 'adam', loss = 'categorical_crossentropy', metrics = [ 'accuracy' ] )

a = tensorflow.keras.callbacks.ModelCheckpoint(filepath='model.h5', monitor='val_loss', save_best_only=True)
b = keras.callbacks.EarlyStopping(monitor = 'val_accuracy', patience=20)

history_8888664 = model.fit(
    x=train_dataset,
    validation_data=validation_dataset,
    callbacks=[a, b],
    steps_per_epoch=30, #1000 images / batch size of 20 = ~50 (https://stackoverflow.com/questions/49922252/choosing-number-of-steps-per-epoch)
    epochs=500)

##plot the learning curve of the overfitted model
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

title = '8x8x8x8x6x6x4 Conv Layers with Maxpooling'

plt.plot(history_8888664.history['accuracy'], "b", label="Training")
plt.plot(history_8888664.history['val_accuracy'], "r", label="Validation")
plt.ylabel('Accuracy')
plt.xlabel('Epoch')
plt.title(title)
plt.legend(loc='lower right')
plt.show()

plt.plot(history_8888664.history['loss'], "b", label="Training")
plt.plot(history_8888664.history['val_loss'], "r", label="Validation")
plt.ylabel('Loss')
plt.xlabel('Epoch')
plt.title(title)
plt.legend(loc='upper right')
plt.show()

##Load the weights of the best model acquired in training
model.load_weights('model.h5')

##Observe the results of the model against the test data
test_loss_8888664, test_acc_8888664 = model.evaluate(
    test_dataset
)

# data_generator = ImageDataGenerator(rescale=1./255, validation_split=0.2)
data_generator = ImageDataGenerator(rescale=1./255)


augmented_generator = ImageDataGenerator(
    # rotation_range=40,
    # width_shift_range=0.2,
    # height_shift_range=0.2,
    # shear_range=0.2,
    # zoom_range=0.2,
    horizontal_flip=True,
    rescale=1./255,
    fill_mode='nearest')



train_dataset = augmented_generator.flow_from_directory(
  # base_dir,
  new_base_dir / "train",
  target_size=(256, 256),
  batch_size=20,
  class_mode='categorical',
  # subset='training',
  color_mode='rgb')

validation_dataset = data_generator.flow_from_directory(
  # base_dir,
  new_base_dir / "validation",
  target_size=(256, 256),
  batch_size=20,
  class_mode='categorical',
  # subset='validation',
  color_mode='rgb')

test_dataset = data_generator.flow_from_directory(
  # base_dir,
  new_base_dir / "test",
  target_size=(256, 256),
  batch_size=20,
  class_mode='categorical',
  # subset='validation',
  color_mode='rgb')



class_dictionary = train_dataset.class_indices
print(class_dictionary)

from keras import callbacks
import tensorflow
import keras

#ok, now lets try this with the validation dataset

model = Sequential()
model.add( Conv2D( 8, ( 3, 3 ), activation = 'relu', input_shape = (256, 256, 3) ) )
model.add( MaxPool2D(4, 4) )
model.add( Conv2D( 6, ( 3, 3 ), activation = 'relu' ) )
model.add( MaxPool2D(4, 4) )
model.add( Conv2D( 4, ( 3, 3 ), activation = 'relu' ) )
model.add( MaxPool2D(4, 4) )
model.add( Conv2D( 4, ( 3, 3 ), activation = 'relu' ) )

model.add( Flatten() )
model.add( Dense( 5, activation = 'relu' ) )
model.add( Dense( 5, activation = 'softmax' ) )
model.summary()

model.compile( optimizer = 'adam', loss = 'categorical_crossentropy', metrics = [ 'accuracy' ] )

a = tensorflow.keras.callbacks.ModelCheckpoint(filepath='model.h5', monitor='val_loss', save_best_only=True)
b = keras.callbacks.EarlyStopping(monitor = 'val_accuracy', patience=20)

history_flip = model.fit(
    x=train_dataset,
    validation_data=validation_dataset,
    callbacks=[a, b],
    steps_per_epoch=30, #1000 images / batch size of 20 = ~50 (https://stackoverflow.com/questions/49922252/choosing-number-of-steps-per-epoch)
    epochs=500)

##plot the learning curve of the overfitted model
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

title = 'Horizontal Flip'

plt.plot(history_flip.history['accuracy'], "b", label="Training")
plt.plot(history_flip.history['val_accuracy'], "r", label="Validation")
plt.ylabel('Accuracy')
plt.xlabel('Epoch')
plt.title(title)
plt.legend(loc='lower right')
plt.show()

plt.plot(history_flip.history['loss'], "b", label="Training")
plt.plot(history_flip.history['val_loss'], "r", label="Validation")
plt.ylabel('Loss')
plt.xlabel('Epoch')
plt.title(title)
plt.legend(loc='upper right')
plt.show()



##Load the weights of the best model acquired in training
model.load_weights('model.h5')

##Observe the results of the model against the test data
test_loss_flip, test_acc_flip = model.evaluate(
    test_dataset,
    steps=23
)

print(f'Test Acc: {test_acc_flip}\nTest Loss: {test_loss_flip}')

from keras import callbacks
import tensorflow
import keras


augmented_generator = ImageDataGenerator(
    # rotation_range=40,
    # width_shift_range=0.2,
    # height_shift_range=0.2,
    # shear_range=0.2,
    zoom_range=0.2,
    # horizontal_flip=True,
    rescale=1./255,
    fill_mode='nearest')



train_dataset = augmented_generator.flow_from_directory(
  # base_dir,
  new_base_dir / "train",
  target_size=(256, 256),
  batch_size=20,
  class_mode='categorical',
  # subset='training',
  color_mode='rgb')

#ok, now lets try this with the validation dataset

model = Sequential()
model.add( Conv2D( 8, ( 3, 3 ), activation = 'relu', input_shape = (256, 256, 3) ) )
model.add( MaxPool2D(4, 4) )
model.add( Conv2D( 6, ( 3, 3 ), activation = 'relu' ) )
model.add( MaxPool2D(4, 4) )
model.add( Conv2D( 4, ( 3, 3 ), activation = 'relu' ) )
model.add( MaxPool2D(4, 4) )
model.add( Conv2D( 4, ( 3, 3 ), activation = 'relu' ) )

model.add( Flatten() )
model.add( Dense( 5, activation = 'relu' ) )
model.add( Dense( 5, activation = 'softmax' ) )
model.summary()

model.compile( optimizer = 'adam', loss = 'categorical_crossentropy', metrics = [ 'accuracy' ] )

a = tensorflow.keras.callbacks.ModelCheckpoint(filepath='model.h5', monitor='val_loss', save_best_only=True)
b = keras.callbacks.EarlyStopping(monitor = 'val_accuracy', patience=20)

history_zoom = model.fit(
    x=train_dataset,
    validation_data=validation_dataset,
    callbacks=[a, b],
    steps_per_epoch=30, #1000 images / batch size of 20 = ~50 (https://stackoverflow.com/questions/49922252/choosing-number-of-steps-per-epoch)
    epochs=500)

##plot the learning curve of the overfitted model
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

title = 'Zoom'

plt.plot(history_zoom.history['accuracy'], "b", label="Training")
plt.plot(history_zoom.history['val_accuracy'], "r", label="Validation")
plt.ylabel('Accuracy')
plt.xlabel('Epoch')
plt.title(title)
plt.legend(loc='lower right')
plt.show()

plt.plot(history_zoom.history['loss'], "b", label="Training")
plt.plot(history_zoom.history['val_loss'], "r", label="Validation")
plt.ylabel('Loss')
plt.xlabel('Epoch')
plt.title(title)
plt.legend(loc='upper right')
plt.show()



##Load the weights of the best model acquired in training
model.load_weights('model.h5')

##Observe the results of the model against the test data
test_loss_zoom, test_acc_zoom = model.evaluate(
    test_dataset,
    steps=23
)

print(f'Test Acc: {test_acc_zoom}\nTest Loss: {test_loss_zoom}')

from keras import callbacks
import tensorflow
import keras


augmented_generator = ImageDataGenerator(
    # rotation_range=40,
    # width_shift_range=0.2,
    # height_shift_range=0.2,
    shear_range=0.2,
    # zoom_range=0.2,
    # horizontal_flip=True,
    rescale=1./255,
    fill_mode='nearest')



train_dataset = augmented_generator.flow_from_directory(
  # base_dir,
  new_base_dir / "train",
  target_size=(256, 256),
  batch_size=20,
  class_mode='categorical',
  # subset='training',
  color_mode='rgb')

#ok, now lets try this with the validation dataset

model = Sequential()
model.add( Conv2D( 8, ( 3, 3 ), activation = 'relu', input_shape = (256, 256, 3) ) )
model.add( MaxPool2D(4, 4) )
model.add( Conv2D( 6, ( 3, 3 ), activation = 'relu' ) )
model.add( MaxPool2D(4, 4) )
model.add( Conv2D( 4, ( 3, 3 ), activation = 'relu' ) )
model.add( MaxPool2D(4, 4) )
model.add( Conv2D( 4, ( 3, 3 ), activation = 'relu' ) )

model.add( Flatten() )
model.add( Dense( 5, activation = 'relu' ) )
model.add( Dense( 5, activation = 'softmax' ) )
model.summary()

model.compile( optimizer = 'adam', loss = 'categorical_crossentropy', metrics = [ 'accuracy' ] )

a = tensorflow.keras.callbacks.ModelCheckpoint(filepath='model.h5', monitor='val_loss', save_best_only=True)
b = keras.callbacks.EarlyStopping(monitor = 'val_accuracy', patience=20)

history_shear = model.fit(
    x=train_dataset,
    validation_data=validation_dataset,
    callbacks=[a, b],
    steps_per_epoch=30, #1000 images / batch size of 20 = ~50 (https://stackoverflow.com/questions/49922252/choosing-number-of-steps-per-epoch)
    epochs=500)

##plot the learning curve of the overfitted model
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

title = 'Shear'

plt.plot(history_shear.history['accuracy'], "b", label="Training")
plt.plot(history_shear.history['val_accuracy'], "r", label="Validation")
plt.ylabel('Accuracy')
plt.xlabel('Epoch')
plt.title(title)
plt.legend(loc='lower right')
plt.show()

plt.plot(history_shear.history['loss'], "b", label="Training")
plt.plot(history_shear.history['val_loss'], "r", label="Validation")
plt.ylabel('Loss')
plt.xlabel('Epoch')
plt.title(title)
plt.legend(loc='upper right')
plt.show()



##Load the weights of the best model acquired in training
model.load_weights('model.h5')

##Observe the results of the model against the test data
test_loss_shear, test_acc_shear = model.evaluate(
    test_dataset,
    steps=23
)

print(f'Test Acc: {test_acc_shear}\nTest Loss: {test_loss_shear}')

from keras import callbacks
import tensorflow
import keras


augmented_generator = ImageDataGenerator(
    # rotation_range=40,
    width_shift_range=0.2,
    height_shift_range=0.2,
    # shear_range=0.2,
    # zoom_range=0.2,
    # horizontal_flip=True,
    rescale=1./255,
    fill_mode='nearest')



train_dataset = augmented_generator.flow_from_directory(
  # base_dir,
  new_base_dir / "train",
  target_size=(256, 256),
  batch_size=20,
  class_mode='categorical',
  # subset='training',
  color_mode='rgb')

#ok, now lets try this with the validation dataset

model = Sequential()
model.add( Conv2D( 8, ( 3, 3 ), activation = 'relu', input_shape = (256, 256, 3) ) )
model.add( MaxPool2D(4, 4) )
model.add( Conv2D( 6, ( 3, 3 ), activation = 'relu' ) )
model.add( MaxPool2D(4, 4) )
model.add( Conv2D( 4, ( 3, 3 ), activation = 'relu' ) )
model.add( MaxPool2D(4, 4) )
model.add( Conv2D( 4, ( 3, 3 ), activation = 'relu' ) )

model.add( Flatten() )
model.add( Dense( 5, activation = 'relu' ) )
model.add( Dense( 5, activation = 'softmax' ) )
model.summary()

model.compile( optimizer = 'adam', loss = 'categorical_crossentropy', metrics = [ 'accuracy' ] )

a = tensorflow.keras.callbacks.ModelCheckpoint(filepath='model.h5', monitor='val_loss', save_best_only=True)
b = keras.callbacks.EarlyStopping(monitor = 'val_accuracy', patience=20)

history_shift = model.fit(
    x=train_dataset,
    validation_data=validation_dataset,
    callbacks=[a, b],
    steps_per_epoch=30, #1000 images / batch size of 20 = ~50 (https://stackoverflow.com/questions/49922252/choosing-number-of-steps-per-epoch)
    epochs=500)

##plot the learning curve of the overfitted model
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

title = 'Shift'

plt.plot(history_shift.history['accuracy'], "b", label="Training")
plt.plot(history_shift.history['val_accuracy'], "r", label="Validation")
plt.ylabel('Accuracy')
plt.xlabel('Epoch')
plt.title(title)
plt.legend(loc='lower right')
plt.show()

plt.plot(history_shift.history['loss'], "b", label="Training")
plt.plot(history_shift.history['val_loss'], "r", label="Validation")
plt.ylabel('Loss')
plt.xlabel('Epoch')
plt.title(title)
plt.legend(loc='upper right')
plt.show()



##Load the weights of the best model acquired in training
model.load_weights('model.h5')

##Observe the results of the model against the test data
test_loss_shift, test_acc_shift = model.evaluate(
    test_dataset,
    steps=23
)

print(f'Test Acc: {test_acc_shift}\nTest Loss: {test_loss_shift}')

from keras import callbacks
import tensorflow
import keras


augmented_generator = ImageDataGenerator(
    rotation_range=40,
    # width_shift_range=0.2,
    # height_shift_range=0.2,
    # shear_range=0.2,
    # zoom_range=0.2,
    # horizontal_flip=True,
    rescale=1./255,
    fill_mode='nearest')



train_dataset = augmented_generator.flow_from_directory(
  # base_dir,
  new_base_dir / "train",
  target_size=(256, 256),
  batch_size=20,
  class_mode='categorical',
  # subset='training',
  color_mode='rgb')

#ok, now lets try this with the validation dataset

model = Sequential()
model.add( Conv2D( 8, ( 3, 3 ), activation = 'relu', input_shape = (256, 256, 3) ) )
model.add( MaxPool2D(4, 4) )
model.add( Conv2D( 6, ( 3, 3 ), activation = 'relu' ) )
model.add( MaxPool2D(4, 4) )
model.add( Conv2D( 4, ( 3, 3 ), activation = 'relu' ) )
model.add( MaxPool2D(4, 4) )
model.add( Conv2D( 4, ( 3, 3 ), activation = 'relu' ) )

model.add( Flatten() )
model.add( Dense( 5, activation = 'relu' ) )
model.add( Dense( 5, activation = 'softmax' ) )
model.summary()

model.compile( optimizer = 'adam', loss = 'categorical_crossentropy', metrics = [ 'accuracy' ] )

a = tensorflow.keras.callbacks.ModelCheckpoint(filepath='model.h5', monitor='val_loss', save_best_only=True)
b = keras.callbacks.EarlyStopping(monitor = 'val_accuracy', patience=20)

history_rotation = model.fit(
    x=train_dataset,
    validation_data=validation_dataset,
    callbacks=[a, b],
    steps_per_epoch=30, #1000 images / batch size of 20 = ~50 (https://stackoverflow.com/questions/49922252/choosing-number-of-steps-per-epoch)
    epochs=500)

##plot the learning curve of the overfitted model
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

title = 'Rotation'

plt.plot(history_rotation.history['accuracy'], "b", label="Training")
plt.plot(history_rotation.history['val_accuracy'], "r", label="Validation")
plt.ylabel('Accuracy')
plt.xlabel('Epoch')
plt.title(title)
plt.legend(loc='lower right')
plt.show()

plt.plot(history_rotation.history['loss'], "b", label="Training")
plt.plot(history_rotation.history['val_loss'], "r", label="Validation")
plt.ylabel('Loss')
plt.xlabel('Epoch')
plt.title(title)
plt.legend(loc='upper right')
plt.show()



##Load the weights of the best model acquired in training
model.load_weights('model.h5')

##Observe the results of the model against the test data
test_loss_rotation, test_acc_rotation = model.evaluate(
    test_dataset,
    steps=23
)

print(f'Test Acc: {test_acc_rotation}\nTest Loss: {test_loss_rotation}')

from keras import callbacks
import tensorflow
import keras


augmented_generator = ImageDataGenerator(
    rotation_range=40,
    width_shift_range=0.2,
    height_shift_range=0.2,
    shear_range=0.2,
    zoom_range=0.2,
    horizontal_flip=True,
    rescale=1./255,
    fill_mode='nearest')



train_dataset = augmented_generator.flow_from_directory(
  # base_dir,
  new_base_dir / "train",
  target_size=(256, 256),
  batch_size=20,
  class_mode='categorical',
  # subset='training',
  color_mode='rgb')

#ok, now lets try this with the validation dataset

model = Sequential()
model.add( Conv2D( 8, ( 3, 3 ), activation = 'relu', input_shape = (256, 256, 3) ) )
model.add( MaxPool2D(4, 4) )
model.add( Conv2D( 6, ( 3, 3 ), activation = 'relu' ) )
model.add( MaxPool2D(4, 4) )
model.add( Conv2D( 4, ( 3, 3 ), activation = 'relu' ) )
model.add( MaxPool2D(4, 4) )
model.add( Conv2D( 4, ( 3, 3 ), activation = 'relu' ) )

model.add( Flatten() )
model.add( Dense( 5, activation = 'relu' ) )
model.add( Dense( 5, activation = 'softmax' ) )
model.summary()

model.compile( optimizer = 'adam', loss = 'categorical_crossentropy', metrics = [ 'accuracy' ] )

a = tensorflow.keras.callbacks.ModelCheckpoint(filepath='model.h5', monitor='val_loss', save_best_only=True)
b = keras.callbacks.EarlyStopping(monitor = 'val_accuracy', patience=20)

history_aug = model.fit(
    x=train_dataset,
    validation_data=validation_dataset,
    callbacks=[a, b],
    steps_per_epoch=30, #1000 images / batch size of 20 = ~50 (https://stackoverflow.com/questions/49922252/choosing-number-of-steps-per-epoch)
    epochs=500)

##plot the learning curve of the overfitted model
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

title = 'Combined Augmentation'

plt.plot(history_aug.history['accuracy'], "b", label="Training")
plt.plot(history_aug.history['val_accuracy'], "r", label="Validation")
plt.ylabel('Accuracy')
plt.xlabel('Epoch')
plt.title(title)
plt.legend(loc='lower right')
plt.show()

plt.plot(history_aug.history['loss'], "b", label="Training")
plt.plot(history_aug.history['val_loss'], "r", label="Validation")
plt.ylabel('Loss')
plt.xlabel('Epoch')
plt.title(title)
plt.legend(loc='upper right')
plt.show()



##Load the weights of the best model acquired in training
model.load_weights('model.h5')

##Observe the results of the model against the test data
test_loss_aug, test_acc_aug = model.evaluate(
    test_dataset,
    steps=23
)

print(f'Test Acc: {test_acc_aug}\nTest Loss: {test_loss_aug}')

from keras import callbacks
import tensorflow
import keras


augmented_generator = ImageDataGenerator(
    rotation_range=40,
    # width_shift_range=0.2,
    # height_shift_range=0.2,
    # shear_range=0.2,
    # zoom_range=0.2,
    horizontal_flip=True,
    rescale=1./255,
    fill_mode='nearest')



train_dataset = augmented_generator.flow_from_directory(
  # base_dir,
  new_base_dir / "train",
  target_size=(256, 256),
  batch_size=20,
  class_mode='categorical',
  # subset='training',
  color_mode='rgb')

#ok, now lets try this with the validation dataset

model = Sequential()
model.add( Conv2D( 8, ( 3, 3 ), activation = 'relu', input_shape = (256, 256, 3) ) )
model.add( MaxPool2D(4, 4) )
model.add( Conv2D( 6, ( 3, 3 ), activation = 'relu' ) )
model.add( MaxPool2D(4, 4) )
model.add( Conv2D( 4, ( 3, 3 ), activation = 'relu' ) )
model.add( MaxPool2D(4, 4) )
model.add( Conv2D( 4, ( 3, 3 ), activation = 'relu' ) )

model.add( Flatten() )
model.add( Dense( 5, activation = 'relu' ) )
model.add( Dense( 5, activation = 'softmax' ) )
model.summary()

model.compile( optimizer = 'adam', loss = 'categorical_crossentropy', metrics = [ 'accuracy' ] )

a = tensorflow.keras.callbacks.ModelCheckpoint(filepath='model.h5', monitor='val_loss', save_best_only=True)
b = keras.callbacks.EarlyStopping(monitor = 'val_accuracy', patience=20)

history_best = model.fit(
    x=train_dataset,
    validation_data=validation_dataset,
    callbacks=[a, b],
    steps_per_epoch=30, #1000 images / batch size of 20 = ~50 (https://stackoverflow.com/questions/49922252/choosing-number-of-steps-per-epoch)
    epochs=500)

##plot the learning curve of the overfitted model
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

title = 'Flip and Rotation Combined'

plt.plot(history_best.history['accuracy'], "b", label="Training")
plt.plot(history_best.history['val_accuracy'], "r", label="Validation")
plt.ylabel('Accuracy')
plt.xlabel('Epoch')
plt.title(title)
plt.legend(loc='lower right')
plt.show()

plt.plot(history_best.history['loss'], "b", label="Training")
plt.plot(history_best.history['val_loss'], "r", label="Validation")
plt.ylabel('Loss')
plt.xlabel('Epoch')
plt.title(title)
plt.legend(loc='upper right')
plt.show()



##Load the weights of the best model acquired in training
model.load_weights('model.h5')

##Observe the results of the model against the test data
test_loss_best, test_acc_best = model.evaluate(
    test_dataset,
    steps=23
)

print(f'Test Acc: {test_acc_best}\nTest Loss: {test_loss_best}')

from keras import callbacks
import tensorflow
import keras


augmented_generator = ImageDataGenerator(
    rotation_range=5,
    width_shift_range=0.05,
    height_shift_range=0.05,
    shear_range=0.05,
    zoom_range=0.05,
    horizontal_flip=True,
    rescale=1./255,
    fill_mode='nearest')



train_dataset = augmented_generator.flow_from_directory(
  # base_dir,
  new_base_dir / "train",
  target_size=(256, 256),
  batch_size=20,
  class_mode='categorical',
  # subset='training',
  color_mode='rgb')

#ok, now lets try this with the validation dataset

model = Sequential()
model.add( Conv2D( 8, ( 3, 3 ), activation = 'relu', input_shape = (256, 256, 3) ) )
model.add( BatchNormalization())
model.add( MaxPool2D(4, 4) )
model.add( Conv2D( 6, ( 3, 3 ), activation = 'relu' ) )
model.add( MaxPool2D(4, 4) )
model.add( Conv2D( 4, ( 3, 3 ), activation = 'relu' ) )
model.add( MaxPool2D(4, 4) )
model.add( Conv2D( 4, ( 3, 3 ), activation = 'relu' ) )

model.add( Flatten() )
model.add( Dense( 5, activation = 'relu' ) )
model.add( Dense( 5, activation = 'softmax' ) )
model.summary()

model.compile( optimizer = 'adam', loss = 'categorical_crossentropy', metrics = [ 'accuracy' ] )

a = tensorflow.keras.callbacks.ModelCheckpoint(filepath='model.h5', monitor='val_loss', save_best_only=True)
b = keras.callbacks.EarlyStopping(monitor = 'val_accuracy', patience=20)

history_batchnormalization = model.fit(
    x=train_dataset,
    validation_data=validation_dataset,
    callbacks=[a, b],
    steps_per_epoch=30, #1000 images / batch size of 20 = ~50 (https://stackoverflow.com/questions/49922252/choosing-number-of-steps-per-epoch)
    epochs=500)

##plot the learning curve of the overfitted model
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

title = 'Batch Normalization'

plt.plot(history_batchnormalization.history['accuracy'], "b", label="Training")
plt.plot(history_batchnormalization.history['val_accuracy'], "r", label="Validation")
plt.ylabel('Accuracy')
plt.xlabel('Epoch')
plt.title(title)
plt.legend(loc='lower right')
plt.show()

plt.plot(history_batchnormalization.history['loss'], "b", label="Training")
plt.plot(history_batchnormalization.history['val_loss'], "r", label="Validation")
plt.ylabel('Loss')
plt.xlabel('Epoch')
plt.title(title)
plt.legend(loc='upper right')
plt.show()

model.load_weights('model.h5')

##Observe the results of the model against the test data

    test_dataset,
    steps=23
)

print(f'Test Acc: {test_loss_bn}\nTest Loss: {test_acc_bn}')

from keras import callbacks
import tensorflow
import keras


augmented_generator = ImageDataGenerator(
    rotation_range=5,
    width_shift_range=0.05,
    height_shift_range=0.05,
    shear_range=0.05,
    zoom_range=0.05,
    horizontal_flip=True,
    rescale=1./255,
    fill_mode='nearest')



train_dataset = augmented_generator.flow_from_directory(
  # base_dir,
  new_base_dir / "train",
  target_size=(256, 256),
  batch_size=20,
  class_mode='categorical',
  # subset='training',
  color_mode='rgb')

#ok, now lets try this with the validation dataset

model = Sequential()
model.add( Conv2D( 8, ( 3, 3 ), activation = 'relu', input_shape = (256, 256, 3) ) )
model.add( Dropout(rate = 0.25))
model.add( MaxPool2D(4, 4) )
model.add( Conv2D( 6, ( 3, 3 ), activation = 'relu' ) )
model.add( MaxPool2D(4, 4) )
model.add( Conv2D( 4, ( 3, 3 ), activation = 'relu' ) )
model.add( MaxPool2D(4, 4) )
model.add( Conv2D( 4, ( 3, 3 ), activation = 'relu' ) )

model.add( Flatten() )
model.add( Dense( 5, activation = 'relu' ) )
model.add( Dense( 5, activation = 'softmax' ) )
model.summary()

model.compile( optimizer = 'adam', loss = 'categorical_crossentropy', metrics = [ 'accuracy' ] )

a = tensorflow.keras.callbacks.ModelCheckpoint(filepath='model.h5', monitor='val_loss', save_best_only=True)
b = keras.callbacks.EarlyStopping(monitor = 'val_accuracy', patience=12)

history_dropout = model.fit(
    x=train_dataset,
    validation_data=validation_dataset,
    callbacks=[a, b],
    steps_per_epoch=30, #1000 images / batch size of 20 = ~50 (https://stackoverflow.com/questions/49922252/choosing-number-of-steps-per-epoch)
    epochs=500)

##plot the learning curve of the overfitted model
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

title = 'Dropout'

plt.plot(history_dropout.history['accuracy'], "b", label="Training")
plt.plot(history_dropout.history['val_accuracy'], "r", label="Validation")
plt.ylabel('Accuracy')
plt.xlabel('Epoch')
plt.title(title)
plt.legend(loc='lower right')
plt.show()

plt.plot(history_dropout.history['loss'], "b", label="Training")
plt.plot(history_dropout.history['val_loss'], "r", label="Validation")
plt.ylabel('Loss')
plt.xlabel('Epoch')
plt.title(title)
plt.legend(loc='upper right')
plt.show()



##Load the weights of the best model acquired in training
model.load_weights('model.h5')

##Observe the results of the model against the test data
test_loss_dropout, test_acc_dropout = model.evaluate(
    test_dataset,
    steps=23
)

print(f'Test Acc: {test_loss_dropout}\nTest Loss: {test_acc_dropout}')

from keras import callbacks
import tensorflow
import keras


augmented_generator = ImageDataGenerator(
    rotation_range=5,
    width_shift_range=0.05,
    height_shift_range=0.05,
    shear_range=0.05,
    zoom_range=0.05,
    horizontal_flip=True,
    rescale=1./255,
    fill_mode='nearest')



train_dataset = augmented_generator.flow_from_directory(
  # base_dir,
  new_base_dir / "train",
  target_size=(256, 256),
  batch_size=20,
  class_mode='categorical',
  # subset='training',
  color_mode='rgb')

#ok, now lets try this with the validation dataset

model = Sequential()
model.add( Conv2D( 8, ( 3, 3 ), kernel_regularizer = regularizers.l2(0.001), activation = 'relu', input_shape = (256, 256, 3) ) )
model.add( MaxPool2D(4, 4) )
model.add( Conv2D( 6, ( 3, 3 ), activation = 'relu' ) )
model.add( MaxPool2D(4, 4) )
model.add( Conv2D( 4, ( 3, 3 ), activation = 'relu' ) )
model.add( MaxPool2D(4, 4) )
model.add( Conv2D( 4, ( 3, 3 ), activation = 'relu' ) )

model.add( Flatten() )
model.add( Dense( 5, activation = 'relu' ) )
model.add( Dense( 5, activation = 'softmax' ) )
model.summary()

model.compile( optimizer = 'adam', loss = 'categorical_crossentropy', metrics = [ 'accuracy' ] )

a = tensorflow.keras.callbacks.ModelCheckpoint(filepath='model.h5', monitor='val_loss', save_best_only=True)
b = keras.callbacks.EarlyStopping(monitor = 'val_accuracy', patience=12)

history_l2 = model.fit(
    x=train_dataset,
    validation_data=validation_dataset,
    callbacks=[a, b],
    steps_per_epoch=30, #1000 images / batch size of 20 = ~50 (https://stackoverflow.com/questions/49922252/choosing-number-of-steps-per-epoch)
    epochs=500)

##plot the learning curve of the overfitted model
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

title = 'L2 Regularization'

plt.plot(history_l2.history['accuracy'], "b", label="Training")
plt.plot(history_l2.history['val_accuracy'], "r", label="Validation")
plt.ylabel('Accuracy')
plt.xlabel('Epoch')
plt.title(title)
plt.legend(loc='lower right')
plt.show()

plt.plot(history_l2.history['loss'], "b", label="Training")
plt.plot(history_l2.history['val_loss'], "r", label="Validation")
plt.ylabel('Loss')
plt.xlabel('Epoch')
plt.title(title)
plt.legend(loc='upper right')
plt.show()



##Load the weights of the best model acquired in training
model.load_weights('model.h5')

##Observe the results of the model against the test data
test_loss_l2, test_acc_l2 = model.evaluate(
    test_dataset,
    steps=23
)

print(f'Test Acc: {test_loss_l2}\nTest Loss: {test_acc_l2}')
